            <div type="bibliography" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange>22A</citedRange></bibl> (<bibl><ptr target="#Vecchio2019"/>, <citedRange>111</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Laes"/>, <citedRange>186 n. 22, 193 n. 58</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/> <citedRange>22A</citedRange></bibl>;) <bibl><ptr target="#Τομαντείοτωνήχων"/> <citedRange>88 no 78 (I. Katsadima)</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Dodonaios"/>, <citedRange>279 no 28 (I. Katsadima)</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                    <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#Meyer2017"/>, <citedRange>152</citedRange> (on slaves in the oracular tablets)</bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Katsadima2023"/>, <citedRange> 52</citedRange> (photograph)</bibl>.</p>
                </div>
<div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
    <ab>
        <lb n="1"/>περὶ <persName><name nymRef="#Κορυδάλλας">Κορυδάλλας</name></persName> καὶ τῶν <persName><name nymRef="#Κορυδάλλα">Κορυδάλλα</name></persName>
        <lb n="2" break="no"/>ς παίδων πότερά κα τυγχάνοιμι 
        <lb n="3"/>πεπαμένος καθάπερ πατήρ; <space extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
        </ab>
</div>
            <div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
    <app loc="l. 1"><rdg resp="#IDodoneDVC">
            Κορυ<supplied reason="omitted">δ</supplied><unclear>ά</unclear>λλας</rdg> <note> and Katsadima, in <ptr target="#Τομαντείοτωνήχων"/></note> <rdg>Κορυδ<unclear>ά</unclear>λλας</rdg> <note>Katsadima, in <ptr target="#Dodonaios"/>.</note> <note>In the photograph, both the delta in the fold and the horizontal bar of the alpha are visible.</note>
    </app>
</div>
            
  <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
     <p>About Korydallas and the children of Korydalla, would I be successful purchasing them just as a father?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
        <p>Sobre Coridala y los hijos de Coridala, ¿tendría éxito si los comprara, como un padre?</p>
        </div>
                <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en"> 
                <p>On the productive lexical family of <foreign xml:lang="grc">πάομαι</foreign> (Att.-Ion. <foreign xml:lang="grc">κτάομαι</foreign>) in the oracular tablets, see <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2007"/>, <citedRange>302-304</citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><ptr target="#MéndezDosuna2024"/>, <citedRange>§ 4.1</citedRange></bibl>. Lhôte (<bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/></bibl>) suggests that this is the same consultant as in <foreign xml:lang="la">I. Dodone Online</foreign> <ref target="i-dodone-online-19a">19A</ref>, but the identification remains speculative.</p>
     
<p n="Ithaca results">The model identifies Epirus as the most likely provenance of the inscription, assigning it a probability of 87.90%. The chronological distribution reaches its maximum in 350-340 BC, with a probability of 16.40%. As for the restoration, καθάπερ (l. 3) is ranked first with overwhelming confidence. The remaining nineteen hypotheses must be rejected, as they are not linguistically valid Greek restorations. See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline22A_2026_06_24.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline22A.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline22A_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
                </div>
